        <section>
            <section.front>
                <doc.title toc-guid="I94cba213e1e311da9c26e67ca3b71335">
                    <head parent="doc.title">
                        <bop/>
                        <bos/>
                        <label.name>§</label.name>
                        <label.designator>2:1.</label.designator>
                        <headtext>Statutory creation of the Panel</headtext>
                        <eos/>
                        <eop/>
                    </head>
                </doc.title>
            </section.front>
            <section.body>
                <para>
                    <bop/>
                    <bos/>
                    <paratext>The Panel originated with the adoption of the multidistrict venue statute, <cite.query
                            w-src-number="0304913943" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="LQ"
                            w-normalized-cite="28USCAS1407" w-pub-number="1000546"
                            ID="I075c59c0680811e8865b9f61650dcdcd">28 U.S.C.A. § 1407</cite.query>, in 1968.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>This statute was the result of lobbying by various groups interested in the improvement of
                        the federal judicial system.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>In the 1960s the need for some tool to permit the management of federal court cases on a
                        nationwide basis became evident during the pendency of numerous civil antitrust cases relating
                        to the electrical equipment industry.
                        <eos/>
                        <bos/>The Judiciary had dealt with these cases on an ad hoc basis while they were pending, but
                        became aware of the need for a more comprehensive means of dealing with massive litigation.
                        <eos/>
                    </paratext>
                    <eop/>
                </para>
            </section.body>
